11:19.637 --> 11:21.347
and he hasn't been able
to do that,

11:21.347 --> 11:23.641
and now he's using big blue
and hitting the steel

11:23.641 --> 11:25.685
as it's well below
forging temperature.

11:25.685 --> 11:27.312
<i>‐ I feel funny.</i>

11:27.312 --> 11:31.399
I'm feeling not myself.
I can't see very well.

11:31.399 --> 11:35.945
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:35.945 --> 11:37.864
‐ Jon's steel just fell apart.

11:37.864 --> 11:39.574
‐ Oh, wow.
‐ Just fell apart on big blue.

11:39.574 --> 11:41.034
‐ Oh, wow.

11:41.034 --> 11:43.328
As time ticks down
on the clock,

11:43.328 --> 11:44.913
if something like that happens,

11:44.913 --> 11:48.291
it can be a devastating moment
for any smith.

11:48.291 --> 11:51.461
<i>‐ I can't catch my breath.</i>
<i>I'm having memory lapses.</i>

11:51.461 --> 11:53.880
I know something's
not right with me.

11:53.880 --> 11:55.673
‐ Man, Jon's hurting right now.
‐ Yeah.

11:57.884 --> 11:59.886
‐ What's going on?
‐ You okay, Jon?

11:59.886 --> 12:01.054
‐ Why don't you come with me?

12:01.054 --> 12:02.055
I want you to come
with me, okay?

12:02.055 --> 12:03.514
Can you get up and walk?

12:03.514 --> 12:06.893
‐ Yes.
‐ Why don't you come with me?

12:06.893 --> 12:09.103
Okay, it's all right.
Just breathe.

12:09.103 --> 12:10.772
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:10.772 --> 12:12.732
‐ The medic has just come out
to the floor,

12:12.732 --> 12:14.901
grabbed Jon,
pulled him off the floor.

12:14.901 --> 12:17.528
‐ Do you feel nausea?
‐ Yeah.

12:17.528 --> 12:20.365
‐ Just hold on a little while.

12:20.365 --> 12:22.659
‐ There's about 45 minutes
left on the clock.

12:22.659 --> 12:24.744
All of our bladesmiths
are working towards

12:24.744 --> 12:27.872
completing their blades
with the exception of Jon.

12:27.872 --> 12:30.708
He's sitting with
our forge medic right now.

12:30.708 --> 12:32.752
‐ It's hard to watch.

12:32.752 --> 12:35.546
<i>‐ It's important to get heat</i>
<i>treat with time on the clock,</i>

12:35.546 --> 12:38.633
because if there's any warpage,
I can fix it.

12:38.633 --> 12:40.593
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:40.593 --> 12:43.388
<i>I pulled it out of the quench.</i>
<i>There are no tings.</i>

12:43.388 --> 12:45.890
<i>There are no cracks.</i>
<i>There are no warps.</i>

12:45.890 --> 12:48.893
I am a very happy camper
right now.

12:48.893 --> 12:50.770
‐ Seth's blade is actually
looking pretty decent

12:50.770 --> 12:52.981
from what I can see over here.
‐ Yeah.

12:52.981 --> 12:55.441
<i>‐ When I pull this knife out</i>
<i>of the etch, flat‐out,</i>

12:55.441 --> 12:56.901
<i>I am not seeing</i>
<i>the ladder pattern</i>

12:56.901 --> 12:59.279
<i>that I was hoping</i>
<i>to have gotten,</i>

12:59.279 --> 13:01.447
and my heart sinks.

13:01.447 --> 13:03.992
<i>This could be a disqualifier.</i>

13:03.992 --> 13:05.952
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:05.952 --> 13:08.413
‐ Your heartbeat is very fast.

13:08.413 --> 13:10.707
‐ All right,
Jon's a medical drop.

13:10.707 --> 13:12.458
We've got EMS
in here right now.

13:12.458 --> 13:14.127
They're gonna load him
in an ambulance.

13:14.127 --> 13:16.004
They're gonna take him
to the emergency room.

13:16.004 --> 13:18.172
It's better to be safe
than sorry.

13:18.172 --> 13:21.426
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:21.426 --> 13:23.428
[siren wailing]

13:23.428 --> 13:25.471
Jon is gonna be okay.

13:25.471 --> 13:28.850
However, the fact that Jon
has left this competition

13:28.850 --> 13:33.187
does not guarantee that all of
these smiths will move forward.

13:33.187 --> 13:34.981
In order to stay
in this competition,

13:34.981 --> 13:38.818
our three bladesmiths still
need to complete their blades.

13:38.818 --> 13:40.820
Bladesmiths, 20 minutes!

13:40.820 --> 13:42.613
‐ I don't have an option
for this quench

13:42.613 --> 13:45.116
not going right
the first time.

13:45.116 --> 13:46.826
‐ And we got a quench.

13:46.826 --> 13:49.579
<i>‐ No dings,</i>
<i>no cracking noises,</i>

13:49.579 --> 13:50.621
<i>and I look at the blade.</i>

13:50.621 --> 13:53.833
It's straight.
This is great.

13:53.833 --> 13:56.669
<i>I go back and stick this thing</i>
<i>in the etch,</i>

13:56.669 --> 13:58.171
giving it the old fish eye.

13:58.171 --> 14:00.298
<i>Looks good.</i>

14:00.298 --> 14:02.008
‐ [chuckles]

14:02.008 --> 14:04.719
‐ Here you go, moment of truth.
Do you see the pattern?

14:04.719 --> 14:06.554
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:06.554 --> 14:08.598
‐ I don't see a ladder.

14:08.598 --> 14:10.516
[bleep].

14:10.516 --> 14:12.018
<i>‐ The quench at this point</i>

14:12.018 --> 14:14.771
<i>is the most important thing</i>
<i>that I can do.</i>

14:14.771 --> 14:16.355
It's hard to see color
right now.

14:16.355 --> 14:19.901
I'm gonna use this magnet,
see how magnetic we are.

14:19.901 --> 14:21.861
‐ I don't think a magnet is
gonna stick to that, buddy boy.

14:21.861 --> 14:23.237
‐ So I'm close.

14:23.237 --> 14:26.115
‐ Steve has been keeping
his steel very hot.

14:26.115 --> 14:28.034
‐ And that's a recipe
for stress fractures

14:28.034 --> 14:30.703
and a brittle blade.

14:30.703 --> 14:33.498
<i>‐ I want to see ladder rungs</i>
<i>on both sides of my blade.</i>

14:33.498 --> 14:34.540
<i>That's the goal.</i>

14:34.540 --> 14:35.833
When I pull my blade out,

14:35.833 --> 14:39.295
<i>I can see where there's been</i>
<i>some rungs cut,</i>

14:39.295 --> 14:42.090
but I don't know if it's gonna
satisfy the judges.

14:42.090 --> 14:44.342
<i>There's no time on the clock,</i>
<i>so at this point,</i>

14:44.342 --> 14:46.594
I need to get
my false edge on first,

14:46.594 --> 14:48.179
<i>and then I want</i>
<i>to start getting ready</i>

14:48.179 --> 14:50.723
to get the cutting edge
like it needs to be.

14:50.723 --> 14:52.225
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:52.225 --> 14:53.392
‐ [bleep].

14:53.392 --> 14:54.685
<i>I almost forgot</i>

14:54.685 --> 14:57.730
<i>I have to put a false edge</i>
<i>on this.</i>

14:57.730 --> 15:01.234
I remembered just as I was
going to turn off the machine,

15:01.234 --> 15:03.736
so now I got to put
the false edge in.

15:03.736 --> 15:08.908
‐ Five, four, three, two, one.

15:08.908 --> 15:10.660
Bladesmiths,
stop what you're doing.

15:10.660 --> 15:11.744
Drop your tools.

15:11.744 --> 15:15.081
This first round
of competition is over.

15:15.081 --> 15:17.458
‐ I'm disappointed that
I didn't alternate my layers

15:17.458 --> 15:20.878
and I didn't cut deep enough
into the steel itself

15:20.878 --> 15:22.588
<i>to get the ladder pattern,</i>

15:22.588 --> 15:26.134
<i>but in this environment it's</i>
<i>very easy to lose yourself</i>

15:26.134 --> 15:30.054
because you get so fixed
on what you want to do

15:30.054 --> 15:33.057
<i>that you don't notice</i>
<i>those types of things,</i>

15:33.057 --> 15:36.727
<i>so I would not be surprised</i>
<i>if they were sending me home.</i>

15:36.727 --> 15:39.105
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
unfortunately,

15:39.105 --> 15:42.400
Jon has medically dropped
from this competition.

15:42.400 --> 15:45.444
That does not absolve you
from the responsibility

15:45.444 --> 15:48.739
of providing us with blades
that fit within the parameters.

15:48.739 --> 15:51.284
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:51.284 --> 15:53.452
You had to make
a signature ladder pattern

15:53.452 --> 15:57.248
Damascus blade between 9
and 12 inches in length

15:57.248 --> 15:59.625
that also included
a false edge.

15:59.625 --> 16:03.004
All right, Seth, please present
your blade to the judges.

16:03.004 --> 16:05.089
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:05.089 --> 16:07.717
<i>‐ First off,</i>
<i>great classic bowie shape.</i>

16:07.717 --> 16:10.636
<i>I like the false edge on here</i>
<i>and the way you put it in,</i>

16:10.636 --> 16:13.639
but there's really
no differentiation.

16:13.639 --> 16:16.309
You can't see any color change
in your etch,

16:16.309 --> 16:17.810
which is pretty much telling me

16:17.810 --> 16:20.271
that the vast majority of metal
on this blade

16:20.271 --> 16:22.481
is all the same metal.

16:22.481 --> 16:25.026
When you take a bunch of layers
of the same metal

16:25.026 --> 16:28.112
and forge weld them together,
that's called a hada technique.

16:28.112 --> 16:30.656
There's certainly
no visible ladder pattern here,

16:30.656 --> 16:35.494
and calling it a Damascus
isn't quite appropriate.

16:35.494 --> 16:37.330
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:37.330 --> 16:38.789
‐ All right, Shaun,
you're up next.

16:38.789 --> 16:40.458
Please present your blade
to the judges.

16:40.458 --> 16:42.627
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:42.627 --> 16:44.545
‐ All right, Shaun,
right off the bat,

16:44.545 --> 16:47.131
there are no ladder patterns
that we're looking for.

16:47.131 --> 16:48.841
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:48.841 --> 16:50.968
This is what I see.
I see a knife shape.

16:50.968 --> 16:52.470
I see a blade
that's got a handle

16:52.470 --> 16:54.347
that looks like
it's gonna slash.

16:54.347 --> 16:56.390
It does have the false edge
we're looking for,

16:56.390 --> 16:59.852
and it's got some layers,
so it's Damascus.

16:59.852 --> 17:01.520
Good job on that,

17:01.520 --> 17:05.024
but we don't have
the ladder pattern.

17:05.024 --> 17:08.819
‐ Steve, if your blade
has a ladder pattern in it

17:08.819 --> 17:10.446
and it hits those parameters,

17:10.446 --> 17:12.156
you could be
the "Forged in Fire" champion

17:12.156 --> 17:14.533
right here, right now.

17:14.533 --> 17:16.869
Please present your blade
to the judges.

17:16.869 --> 17:23.876
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:23.876 --> 17:26.504
How about it, J?
Is Steve our new champion?

17:26.504 --> 17:30.550
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:30.550 --> 17:33.219
‐ No.
‐ Damn.

17:33.219 --> 17:35.555
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:35.555 --> 17:38.057
<i>‐ Steve, instead of</i>
<i>alternating your layers,</i>

17:38.057 --> 17:41.060
you stacked up your 15N20
and forge welded it together,

17:41.060 --> 17:43.187
<i>which would be a hada.</i>

17:43.187 --> 17:45.439
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:45.439 --> 17:47.692
‐ Bladesmiths, this is not
the first time

17:47.692 --> 17:49.193
that one of your competitors

17:49.193 --> 17:51.195
has medically dropped
from the competition,

17:51.195 --> 17:52.738
and it's not the first time
that a bladesmith

17:52.738 --> 17:55.449
hasn't made parameters,
but it is the first time

17:55.449 --> 17:58.286
that all of our bladesmiths
missed the parameters,

17:58.286 --> 18:01.414
so somehow those two negatives
multiplied together

18:01.414 --> 18:03.416
have come out to a positive,

18:03.416 --> 18:06.419
and that's that you three will
be continuing into round two

18:06.419 --> 18:09.088
in spite of your patterns.

18:09.088 --> 18:11.382
‐ Oh, thank goodness.

18:11.382 --> 18:13.676
‐ Now that your blades
have been tempered,

18:13.676 --> 18:15.761
it's time to turn them
into fully functional weapons

18:15.761 --> 18:17.430
by attaching handles to them.

18:17.430 --> 18:19.557
You have two hours in which
to complete your work.

18:19.557 --> 18:21.559
After this round,
your blades will be tested

18:21.559 --> 18:24.812
for strength and durability
in a bone chop,

18:24.812 --> 18:28.232
then for edge retention
in a ham slice.

18:28.232 --> 18:30.610
It's time to put the failures
of round one behind you

18:30.610 --> 18:34.780
and prove yourselves to be the
craftsmen you are in round two.

18:34.780 --> 18:38.993
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your two hours starts now.

18:38.993 --> 18:40.786
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:40.786 --> 18:42.747
<i>‐ Being able to make it</i>
<i>to round two</i>

18:42.747 --> 18:44.624
is an absolute blessing,

18:44.624 --> 18:46.876
because I didn't meet
the parameters

18:46.876 --> 18:48.252
of what the judges wanted,

18:48.252 --> 18:51.464
<i>but luckily, we went on</i>
<i>to the next round.</i>

18:51.464 --> 18:53.633
‐ Well, this is a good move
on Seth's part.

18:53.633 --> 18:55.468
There's only two hours
on the clock.

18:55.468 --> 18:58.179
Go ahead and get the handle
on that blade,

18:58.179 --> 19:00.931
because he's far enough along
coming out of round one

19:00.931 --> 19:02.683
that he's gonna have
plenty of time

19:02.683 --> 19:05.811
to put an edge on that blade.
‐ Oh, yeah.

19:05.811 --> 19:06.937
<i>‐ It's crucial to make sure</i>

19:06.937 --> 19:08.314
<i>that you pick</i>
<i>the right material</i>

19:08.314 --> 19:10.149
<i>and that it all fits together</i>

19:10.149 --> 19:13.194
and that there are
hardly any gaps.

19:13.194 --> 19:16.364
‐ You can see Seth trying to
fit up that antler to his tang.

19:16.364 --> 19:19.241
It's not quite making the fit
that he wants,

19:19.241 --> 19:20.534
but it doesn't look like
he drilled

19:20.534 --> 19:21.786
all the way through
that antler.

19:21.786 --> 19:22.995
‐ No, it doesn't.

19:22.995 --> 19:25.289
<i>‐ I have at least</i>
<i>a 1/2‐inch space</i>

19:25.289 --> 19:28.292
between where my guard
and spacers are.

19:28.292 --> 19:32.463
<i>I really need to get this</i>
<i>fixed quickly.</i>

19:32.463 --> 19:34.298
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:34.298 --> 19:37.301
‐ Looks like Shaun has chosen
some handle material over here.

19:37.301 --> 19:39.845
<i>‐ It looks like a rosewood,</i>
<i>maybe Bavarian rosewood.</i>

19:39.845 --> 19:42.306
I've worked with a lot
of different woods before.

19:42.306 --> 19:45.351
<i>Hardwoods usually are a good</i>
<i>choice unless they're brittle,</i>

19:45.351 --> 19:48.145
<i>but this is a nice,</i>
<i>tough hardwood.</i>

19:48.145 --> 19:49.647
<i>I get the two scales</i>
<i>of wood fitted.</i>

19:49.647 --> 19:51.565
<i>I'm gonna mix some epoxy.</i>

19:51.565 --> 19:54.318
‐ He's gonna glue those slabs
on and then drill through them.

19:54.318 --> 19:56.904
‐ That's backwards, right?

19:56.904 --> 19:58.197
‐ It can be done,

19:58.197 --> 20:00.491
but you're putting
all your eggs in one basket.

20:00.491 --> 20:01.659
If the drilling goes badly,

20:01.659 --> 20:02.868
you have to throw away
your scales

20:02.868 --> 20:04.870
and start over again.

20:04.870 --> 20:07.707
‐ This is a [bleep] mess.
Aw, [bleep].

20:07.707 --> 20:09.208
<i>It should not be this hard.</i>

20:09.208 --> 20:11.043
It's not this hard
when I'm doing it on my own.

20:11.043 --> 20:15.381
<i>Struggling aside, I have</i>
<i>clamped my scales to my blade.</i>

20:15.381 --> 20:17.383
<i>‐ At this point,</i>
<i>I've written a schedule down</i>

20:17.383 --> 20:18.718
<i>on my workstation,</i>

20:18.718 --> 20:21.220
<i>and I'm gonna follow</i>
<i>that schedule to the T,</i>

20:21.220 --> 20:23.889
so my goal first
is to run to the grinder

20:23.889 --> 20:25.725
<i>and get the 36‐grit belt</i>

20:25.725 --> 20:28.394
and get the big wheel,
turn up the speed to high,

20:28.394 --> 20:30.563
<i>and just grind</i>
<i>as much metal as I can.</i>

20:30.563 --> 20:32.231
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:32.231 --> 20:34.942
‐ Steve's got a lot
of those cut marks

20:34.942 --> 20:37.570
from when he attempted
the ladder pattern,

20:37.570 --> 20:40.448
and he's got a huge amount
of steel on the handle...

20:40.448 --> 20:42.700
‐ Right.
‐ To grind down.

20:42.700 --> 20:44.577
‐ I'm hoping that this
doesn't take too long.

20:44.577 --> 20:47.246
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:47.246 --> 20:48.748
<i>‐ I'm finally back in action.</i>

20:48.748 --> 20:50.708
<i>I got my handle dry fit up.</i>

20:50.708 --> 20:52.418
Nice.

20:52.418 --> 20:55.755
‐ Seth is in the hole position
as far as getting this done.

20:55.755 --> 20:57.757
He's got his epoxy set up.

20:57.757 --> 21:00.760
He's got his handle material.
He's moving right along.

21:00.760 --> 21:01.802
<i>‐ Gluing up the handle</i>

21:01.802 --> 21:03.929
is always a little bit
frustrating,

21:03.929 --> 21:06.432
<i>waiting for it to dry.</i>

21:06.432 --> 21:08.267
<i>‐ Right now</i>
<i>it's just epoxied on,</i>

21:08.267 --> 21:09.894
and whenever it gets dry,

21:09.894 --> 21:12.396
I'm gonna bring it over
to the drill press

21:12.396 --> 21:14.190
and drill a pin in
through there.

21:14.190 --> 21:17.443
I just have to stay patient,
and that's a huge hurdle.

21:17.443 --> 21:20.154
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:20.154 --> 21:21.447
<i>‐ My scales are attached.</i>

21:21.447 --> 21:24.241
<i>I need to get</i>
<i>my pin holes drilled.</i>

21:24.241 --> 21:26.911
<i>I can't drill</i>
<i>through the metal.</i>

21:26.911 --> 21:28.621
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:28.621 --> 21:30.414
Come on, baby.

21:30.414 --> 21:31.582
This is either
a really hard blade

21:31.582 --> 21:34.460
or I'm using really dull bits.

21:34.460 --> 21:36.545
Hard to tell
what's even going on here.

21:36.545 --> 21:38.631
[metal grinding]

21:38.631 --> 21:41.008
It goes nowhere.
‐ No, really?

21:41.008 --> 21:42.426
‐ I can't drill
through the blade.

21:42.426 --> 21:44.762
It's just [bleep] ridiculous.

21:44.762 --> 21:47.306
Running out of time.

21:47.306 --> 21:48.682
<i>And then it hits me.</i>

21:48.682 --> 21:51.268
It's simple, two words:
bada‐bing.

21:51.268 --> 21:54.897
I am putting in four fake pins.

21:54.897 --> 21:57.358
‐ Now, we have had blades
turned in

21:57.358 --> 21:59.151
that just have
a glued‐on handle,

21:59.151 --> 22:00.820
and they've performed well.

22:00.820 --> 22:02.446
‐ That was usually on
a hidden tang knife, though.

22:02.446 --> 22:03.823
‐ Okay.

22:03.823 --> 22:06.450
‐ During the bone chop,
if this epoxy fails,

22:06.450 --> 22:09.495
there is nothing to keep
the handle on the knife.

22:09.495 --> 22:11.121
‐ I wasn't planning
on wearing a glove

22:11.121 --> 22:12.790
during the strength test,
but I am now.

22:12.790 --> 22:15.000
‐ [laughs]

22:15.000 --> 22:18.170
‐ So I've got my handle
the shape and size that I want.

22:18.170 --> 22:20.297
I found some scales
that I like.

22:20.297 --> 22:22.341
Now I'm gonna go get busy
on the drill press.

22:22.341 --> 22:25.970
I want to get this done,
ready to glue.

22:25.970 --> 22:27.429
‐ So Steve has just finished

22:27.429 --> 22:29.139
drilling some holes
in his tang.

22:29.139 --> 22:31.600
He is gonna put
some scales on that.

22:31.600 --> 22:34.353
‐ But he's chosen
those stabilized pinecones

22:34.353 --> 22:36.021
as his slab material.

22:36.021 --> 22:38.858
You grind those too thin,
they become very brittle.

22:38.858 --> 22:40.359
<i>‐ I'm stressing</i>
<i>a little bit here.</i>

22:40.359 --> 22:42.278
I can't get these scales
to go on

22:42.278 --> 22:43.404
the way I want them to.

22:43.404 --> 22:46.490
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:46.490 --> 22:48.450
[cracking]

22:48.450 --> 22:51.203
Handle cracked.

22:51.203 --> 22:52.955
‐ Steve's handle material
just cracked in half.

22:55.708 --> 22:58.127
‐ Pinecone's a nice,
‐ Tgood‐looking stuff

22:58.127 --> 22:59.628
if you know how to work it.

22:59.628 --> 23:01.672
If you don't,
you force it at all,

23:01.672 --> 23:05.968
it follows those veins of
the pinecone itself and cracks.

23:05.968 --> 23:07.970
<i>‐ There's no need to cry</i>
<i>over spilled milk.</i>

23:07.970 --> 23:10.014
I just need to keep
the one scale

23:10.014 --> 23:11.307
that I've already got drilled

23:11.307 --> 23:13.726
<i>and put another one</i>
<i>on the other side.</i>

23:13.726 --> 23:15.895
<i>My knife is gonna have two</i>
<i>different handle materials,</i>

23:15.895 --> 23:17.062
and that's okay.

23:17.062 --> 23:18.522
‐ Bladesmiths,

23:18.522 --> 23:22.818
you have 30 minutes remaining
to finish your work!

23:22.818 --> 23:24.194
<i>‐ I'm at the drill press,</i>

23:24.194 --> 23:25.779
<i>and not too far from me,</i>
<i>I look over,</i>

23:25.779 --> 23:28.908
<i>and I see the bones that Jay</i>
<i>is going to test my knife with</i>

23:28.908 --> 23:31.035
and there's only one of two
things that's gonna happen.

23:31.035 --> 23:33.162
I'm either going to be smiling,

23:33.162 --> 23:37.333
or it's gonna be
a glorious break and failure.

23:37.333 --> 23:38.667
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:38.667 --> 23:40.336
<i>I have to put a pin in this,</i>

23:40.336 --> 23:42.504
and this is always
the little bit nervous part

23:42.504 --> 23:44.506
because it's a hidden tang.

23:44.506 --> 23:46.467
I really hope that
the drill bit

23:46.467 --> 23:48.177
will go through the tang
itself.

23:48.177 --> 23:49.970
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:49.970 --> 23:53.933
As I feel it go through
the metal, relief.

23:53.933 --> 23:55.434
<i>The pin is set.</i>

23:55.434 --> 23:57.519
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:57.519 --> 23:58.646
<i>‐ The knife needs to be sharp.</i>

23:58.646 --> 24:00.189
<i>I got the main bevel on,</i>

24:00.189 --> 24:04.276
and as I'm shaping this handle,
a pin falls out.

24:04.276 --> 24:06.195
Son of a bitch.

24:06.195 --> 24:09.073
‐ Something's going on
with Shaun's handle right now.

24:09.073 --> 24:10.366
‐ Heated it up,
and the glue released.

24:10.366 --> 24:11.408
‐ Yup.

24:11.408 --> 24:13.410
‐ Heat the pin up,
melt the epoxy.

24:13.410 --> 24:14.870
That was dumb.

24:14.870 --> 24:16.205
‐ Ten minutes, bladesmiths.

24:16.205 --> 24:18.624
You have ten minutes remaining
in the round.

24:18.624 --> 24:21.377
<i>‐ My blade's 90% done, and I</i>
<i>just need to get it to 100,</i>

24:21.377 --> 24:23.963
and I want to get it there
real bad.

24:23.963 --> 24:26.590
<i>New plan: I'm gonna coat</i>
<i>this thing in epoxy.</i>

24:26.590 --> 24:27.883
This is the finish.

24:27.883 --> 24:30.719
The finish will be epoxy,
and that's gonna hold.

24:30.719 --> 24:33.764
‐ He's painting it on so his
pins have a coating of epoxy

24:33.764 --> 24:36.308
over the top of them
to keep them from falling out.

24:36.308 --> 24:37.726
Hey.

24:37.726 --> 24:38.978
<i>‐ I got to get this thing</i>
<i>sharp.</i>

24:38.978 --> 24:40.354
<i>I got to get this thing</i>
<i>shaped.</i>

24:40.354 --> 24:42.773
So I'm in a pinch, and I'm
nervous about the test.

24:42.773 --> 24:44.984
I'm nervous
about getting finished.

24:44.984 --> 24:46.986
<i>Just as quickly as I can,</i>

24:46.986 --> 24:49.947
<i>I'm gonna put an edge that'll</i>
<i>perform in the test, I hope.</i>

24:49.947 --> 24:52.908
‐ Five, four, three,

24:52.908 --> 24:54.743
two, one.

24:54.743 --> 24:56.829
Bladesmiths,
stop what you're doing.

24:56.829 --> 25:00.249
This second round
of competition is over.

25:00.249 --> 25:02.292
<i>‐ Round two was tough.</i>
<i>Not much went my way,</i>

25:02.292 --> 25:04.378
<i>but I turned in</i>
<i>a finished blade.</i>

25:04.378 --> 25:06.005
<i>I think it's finished.</i>

25:06.005 --> 25:08.007
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:08.007 --> 25:10.592
‐ Bladesmiths, welcome
to the strength test.

25:10.592 --> 25:12.136
I'm gonna take each
of your blades

25:12.136 --> 25:14.805
and beat them mercilessly
into these bones.

25:14.805 --> 25:16.765
I don't really care what
your blades do to the bones.

25:16.765 --> 25:18.809
I want to see what the bones do
to your blades.

25:18.809 --> 25:21.186
Seth, you're up first.
How you feeling?

25:21.186 --> 25:23.689
‐ A little nervous,
but go right ahead.

25:23.689 --> 25:25.858
<i>Chopping into cow bone</i>
<i>can do a lot of things:</i>

25:25.858 --> 25:27.860
<i>ruin the structural integrity</i>
<i>of the blade.</i>

25:27.860 --> 25:30.696
It can chip so bad
or even break.

25:30.696 --> 25:37.703
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:51.842 --> 25:53.677
‐ Well, Seth, you survived.

25:53.677 --> 25:56.388
We do have some chipping,
which I call chewing.

25:56.388 --> 25:59.183
Looks like a mouse chewed
on the edge of your blade,

25:59.183 --> 26:00.559
but everything held up tight.

26:00.559 --> 26:02.436
The handle was comfortable.
Good job.

26:02.436 --> 26:03.854
‐ Thank you, sir.

26:03.854 --> 26:05.981
‐ It's that time, Shaun.
How you feeling?

26:05.981 --> 26:08.358
‐ Well, time will tell now.

26:08.358 --> 26:10.069
<i>I'm having concerns</i>
<i>about my handle.</i>

26:10.069 --> 26:11.445
<i>It's not mechanically</i>
<i>fastened,</i>

26:11.445 --> 26:13.739
<i>but I feel like</i>
<i>the epoxy should hold.</i>

26:13.739 --> 26:16.492
I'm hoping mine survives.

26:16.492 --> 26:23.457
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:29.588 --> 26:31.799
[cracking]
‐ Ooh!

26:31.799 --> 26:38.263
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:38.263 --> 26:39.473
‐ There he goes.

26:39.473 --> 26:45.062
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:45.062 --> 26:46.939
‐ Only epoxy holding this.

26:46.939 --> 26:49.066
You made the mistake
of gluing your scales on,

26:49.066 --> 26:51.026
then trying to drill
all the way through,

26:51.026 --> 26:52.986
and then it was too hard,

26:52.986 --> 26:54.905
so there's no
mechanical connection.

26:54.905 --> 26:56.532
The stress
from those three blows

26:56.532 --> 26:58.450
was enough to pop the scale
right off.

26:58.450 --> 27:02.830
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:02.830 --> 27:04.456
‐ All right, Shaun,
your blade has suffered

27:04.456 --> 27:07.167
a catastrophic failure
in the handle.

27:07.167 --> 27:10.129
However, it doesn't mean
that you're done yet.

27:10.129 --> 27:13.006
Steve, your blade
needs to survive

27:13.006 --> 27:15.050
three strikes against the bone

27:15.050 --> 27:17.136
in order to move forward
in this competition.

27:17.136 --> 27:18.887
You think it can handle it?

27:18.887 --> 27:22.182
‐ I hope so.
‐ All right. J?

27:22.182 --> 27:24.810
<i>‐ My blade has got to survive</i>
<i>this bone chop,</i>

27:24.810 --> 27:26.728
<i>and this is a brutal test.</i>

27:26.728 --> 27:28.981
<i>I'm nervous, but I'm</i>
<i>a little bit more confident</i>

27:28.981 --> 27:31.316
that it only has to survive
three strikes.

27:31.316 --> 27:35.487
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:35.487 --> 27:38.699
If I have a flaw in my metal,
my knife will snap.

27:38.699 --> 27:45.163
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:45.163 --> 27:48.083
‐ Steve, your blade survived
three strikes against the bone,

27:48.083 --> 27:50.669
so that means you'll be moving
forward in this competition.

27:50.669 --> 27:52.754
Unfortunately, Shaun,
your blade

27:52.754 --> 27:54.923
suffered a catastrophic failure
in the handle

27:54.923 --> 27:57.968
and can no longer continue
in this competition.

27:57.968 --> 28:00.345
Please leave the Forge.

28:00.345 --> 28:02.139
<i>‐ I've always been told</i>
<i>your worst mistakes</i>

28:02.139 --> 28:04.016
<i>are your best lessons.</i>

28:04.016 --> 28:07.144
<i>This challenge has really</i>
<i>been, like, a baptism in fire.</i>

28:07.144 --> 28:09.605
If I had more time,
I probably would have decided

28:09.605 --> 28:14.234
to put some mechanical
fastening on that handle.

28:14.234 --> 28:16.069
‐ Seth, Steve, congratulations.

28:16.069 --> 28:18.614
You guys have made it to this
final round of competition,

28:18.614 --> 28:20.908
and that means we're sending
you back to your home forges

28:20.908 --> 28:24.161
to recreate this iconic weapon
from history...

28:24.161 --> 28:26.455
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:26.455 --> 28:28.874
Napoleon's saber.

28:28.874 --> 28:30.292
‐ Ooh.

28:30.292 --> 28:32.544
<i>‐ One of history's most</i>
<i>ingenious military minds,</i>

28:32.544 --> 28:34.546
<i>Napoleon Bonaparte,</i>
<i>was France's emperor</i>

28:34.546 --> 28:37.215
<i>beginning in the early 1800s.</i>

28:37.215 --> 28:39.301
<i>Napoleon revolutionized</i>
<i>battlefield tactics</i>

28:39.301 --> 28:41.345
<i>with the brilliant use</i>
<i>of cannonade</i>

28:41.345 --> 28:43.931
<i>in close coordination</i>
<i>with cavalry.</i>

28:43.931 --> 28:46.183
<i>His lightning‐fast horsemen</i>
<i>carried pistols</i>

28:46.183 --> 28:48.560
<i>and curved sabers</i>
<i>which delivered deadly thrusts</i>

28:48.560 --> 28:51.313
<i>and crippling slashes</i>
<i>in close combat.</i>

28:51.313 --> 28:53.565
<i>In the pivotal Battle</i>
<i>of Marengo, a victory</i>

28:53.565 --> 28:56.068
<i>that assured his political</i>
<i>ascendance in France,</i>

28:56.068 --> 28:58.904
<i>Napoleon carried</i>
<i>this gold‐adorned saber.</i>

28:58.904 --> 29:01.490
Your blade must include
a pommel,

29:01.490 --> 29:04.409
a blade length
between 30 and 32 inches,

29:04.409 --> 29:06.536
and a front clip.

29:06.536 --> 29:09.081
<i>‐ I've never made anything</i>
<i>like Napoleon's saber.</i>

29:09.081 --> 29:11.124
So far that's been the theme
for me,

29:11.124 --> 29:14.002
<i>don't be scared</i>
<i>to try something new.</i>

29:14.002 --> 29:16.380
I'm gonna give it
the $10,000 try.

29:16.380 --> 29:17.798
‐ You'll have four days
at your home forge

29:17.798 --> 29:19.508
in which to complete
this challenge,

29:19.508 --> 29:21.259
and, of course, at the end
of that time, you will return

29:21.259 --> 29:24.096
and present your sabers
to our panel of expert judges,

29:24.096 --> 29:26.056
and after they've tested
the hell out of them,

29:26.056 --> 29:28.016
we'll call one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

29:28.016 --> 29:30.686
and hand you a check
for $10,000.

29:30.686 --> 29:33.814
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in four days.

29:33.814 --> 29:35.774
‐ Good luck.

29:35.774 --> 29:38.694
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:38.694 --> 29:42.072
<i>I'm back home at my home</i>
<i>forge in Gautier, Mississippi,</i>

29:42.072 --> 29:44.825
<i>and I'm going to be working</i>
<i>on Napoleon's saber.</i>

29:44.825 --> 29:47.119
<i>Round one, I let the pressure</i>
<i>get to my head,</i>

29:47.119 --> 29:48.787
and I didn't meet parameters,

29:48.787 --> 29:50.664
<i>so I'm really gonna</i>
<i>have to make sure</i>

29:50.664 --> 29:52.332
<i>that I don't get flustered</i>

29:52.332 --> 29:56.336
<i>and make this thing beautiful</i>
<i>and functional as well.</i>

29:56.336 --> 29:59.631
<i>I decided to go with 5160.</i>

29:59.631 --> 30:02.300
<i>It is a great spring steel,</i>

30:02.300 --> 30:04.511
<i>but I'm looking at the blade,</i>

30:04.511 --> 30:07.639
<i>and I think I have</i>
<i>a little too much curvature.</i>

30:07.639 --> 30:09.641
I was at the 3‐inch mark,

30:09.641 --> 30:12.019
<i>so I had to put it back</i>
<i>in the forge</i>

30:12.019 --> 30:14.938
<i>and knock it down.</i>

30:14.938 --> 30:18.191
I knocked it down
a little too far.

30:18.191 --> 30:20.068
<i>Time to go back</i>
<i>in the forge again.</i>

30:20.068 --> 30:23.155
It's kind of like
a cat and mouse game.

30:23.155 --> 30:25.532
A little over an inch.

30:25.532 --> 30:28.452
<i>Well, it's just</i>
<i>one of those things.</i>

30:28.452 --> 30:30.037
<i>It's back and forth</i>
<i>and back and forth,</i>

30:30.037 --> 30:33.165
and I'm finally...
got it.

30:33.165 --> 30:35.876
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:35.876 --> 30:38.670
‐ I'm back at home.
I'm in my comfort zone.

30:38.670 --> 30:42.007
<i>The lack of power tools could</i>
<i>put me at a disadvantage,</i>

30:42.007 --> 30:43.717
<i>so I need to plan wisely.</i>

30:43.717 --> 30:45.385
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:45.385 --> 30:48.138
<i>I've got a nice bar of 5160.</i>

30:48.138 --> 30:50.515
<i>It's gonna make a good,</i>
<i>strong sword.</i>

30:50.515 --> 30:54.019
<i>It is super hard to hammer,</i>

30:54.019 --> 30:55.812
<i>and I'm gonna have to</i>
<i>just get after it</i>

30:55.812 --> 30:58.482
<i>and know that day one</i>
<i>is gonna be tough,</i>

30:58.482 --> 31:01.151
but I'm gonna have to
suck it up.

31:01.151 --> 31:04.196
We're gonna be here a while.

31:04.196 --> 31:08.533
For the pommel, I'm using
1‐inch solid hot rolled steel.

31:08.533 --> 31:10.619
<i>I've got a lot of metal</i>
<i>to move,</i>

31:10.619 --> 31:12.037
<i>and I'm a little bit worried</i>

31:12.037 --> 31:15.248
<i>that I might not get</i>
<i>all this metal moved today.</i>

31:15.248 --> 31:18.877
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:18.877 --> 31:22.214
<i>Finally I've got this thing</i>
<i>where I need it.</i>

31:22.214 --> 31:25.217
<i>We're at the correct length,</i>
<i>the correct thickness.</i>

31:25.217 --> 31:27.135
Today is a success.

31:27.135 --> 31:29.721
All right.
Feels pretty good.

31:29.721 --> 31:31.765
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:31.765 --> 31:33.600
<i>‐ It's the start of day two.</i>

31:33.600 --> 31:35.602
It's time to move on to the
heat treatment of the blade.

31:35.602 --> 31:36.895
<i>The idea is,</i>

31:36.895 --> 31:41.566
<i>is to get as even a heat</i>
<i>on this as possible,</i>

31:41.566 --> 31:45.278
and like Napoleon,
I will divide and conquer.

31:45.278 --> 31:50.158
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:50.158 --> 31:53.620
<i>I don't feel no ticks.</i>
<i>I don't feel no tings.</i>

31:53.620 --> 31:56.623
<i>I have a hardened blade.</i>

31:56.623 --> 31:58.959
<i>It's time to do a rough fit‐up</i>

31:58.959 --> 32:01.753
<i>of the wood part of the handle</i>
<i>and the pommel,</i>

32:01.753 --> 32:06.591
<i>and this is going to</i>
<i>taper down to brass.</i>

32:06.591 --> 32:11.429
<i>That's the idea.</i>
<i>Now, is it going to work?</i>

32:11.429 --> 32:14.266
<i>I go to try to bend it,</i>
<i>and it bends just a little bit</i>

32:14.266 --> 32:16.143
<i>on the first go‐round,</i>
<i>and I'm like,</i>

32:16.143 --> 32:18.061
"All right, all right, this
looks like it's going to work.

32:20.689 --> 32:23.692
<i>I go to try to bend it</i>
<i>one more time.</i>

32:23.692 --> 32:26.444
Oh!
Mm. Broke the brass.

32:26.444 --> 32:27.988
<i>That was my biggest piece</i>
<i>of brass</i>

32:27.988 --> 32:29.614
<i>that I could have used for it,</i>

32:29.614 --> 32:31.825
<i>so that's kind of</i>
<i>down the drain.</i>

32:31.825 --> 32:34.161
At this point
I don't really know what to do,

32:34.161 --> 32:36.872
<i>but I look down at the floor,</i>

32:36.872 --> 32:39.166
<i>and I'm looking at</i>
<i>the deer antlers that I have,</i>

32:39.166 --> 32:40.959
<i>and I notice</i>
<i>the curvature in them.</i>

32:40.959 --> 32:43.879
No one says that
it has to be made out of brass,

32:43.879 --> 32:45.630
copper, or gold.

32:45.630 --> 32:49.134
<i>As long as I hollow it out</i>
<i>and it has a nice taper to it</i>

32:49.134 --> 32:52.846
and it fits the hand,
why not a deer antler?

32:54.556 --> 32:56.850
We got a fit.

32:56.850 --> 32:58.935
<i>‐ Today we'll be</i>
<i>quenching the blade.</i>

32:58.935 --> 33:01.771
The quench is a moment
that can go horribly wrong.

33:01.771 --> 33:03.648
<i>I've got to get</i>
<i>the entire blade</i>

33:03.648 --> 33:06.026
<i>one nice,</i>
<i>uniform temperature.</i>

33:06.026 --> 33:08.486
It's not gonna be very easy
in the short forge that I have,

33:08.486 --> 33:11.531
so what I plan on doing
is building an oven

33:11.531 --> 33:13.491
<i>at the back side of the forge.</i>

33:13.491 --> 33:15.994
This oven's gonna keep
my point warm

33:15.994 --> 33:17.537
but not let it cool off.

33:17.537 --> 33:19.164
It should be a good help.

33:19.164 --> 33:20.665
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:20.665 --> 33:23.335
<i>So I've got the forge</i>
<i>turned up as high as it'll go.</i>

33:23.335 --> 33:26.379
<i>I've got my little</i>
<i>butane torch in the front.</i>

33:26.379 --> 33:29.007
All right, here we go.

33:29.007 --> 33:36.014
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:36.014 --> 33:38.558
We're straight.

33:38.558 --> 33:40.644
The beautiful sound
of a skating file,

33:40.644 --> 33:42.604
hard, hard, hard.

33:42.604 --> 33:45.523
‐ How'd the quench go?
‐ Quench went good, I think,

33:45.523 --> 33:50.403
no bends, no warps, got it out.
The file skated it on it.

33:50.403 --> 33:52.280
‐ I'm ready to see it finished.

33:52.280 --> 33:53.782
‐ Give me a little while.
We'll have that done, okay?

33:53.782 --> 33:55.242
‐ Okay.
‐ Thanks for checking.

33:55.242 --> 33:56.451
‐ No problem.
‐ Love you.

33:56.451 --> 33:57.702
‐ Love you too.

33:57.702 --> 33:59.371
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:59.371 --> 34:02.457
<i>‐ The closer and closer I get</i>
<i>towards the final shape of it,</i>

34:02.457 --> 34:04.084
<i>I'm feeling it in my hand,</i>

34:04.084 --> 34:05.919
<i>kind of twirling it</i>
<i>a little bit.</i>

34:05.919 --> 34:07.128
<i>Not quite as good</i>

34:07.128 --> 34:09.005
<i>as Doug Marcaida will be</i>
<i>doing, but...</i>

34:09.005 --> 34:11.883
Feels good in
the hand.

34:11.883 --> 34:13.260
<i>Becoming</i>
<i>a "Forged in Fire" champion</i>

34:13.260 --> 34:15.762
<i>would be a great way</i>
<i>to show people</i>

34:15.762 --> 34:19.724
that I can do this
and would be one step closer

34:19.724 --> 34:21.893
to me becoming
a fulltime bladesmith

34:21.893 --> 34:24.980
because this is the‐‐
the dream right here.

34:24.980 --> 34:28.483
I am done.
I couldn't be happier.

34:28.483 --> 34:30.235
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:30.235 --> 34:31.653
<i>‐ It's the last day.</i>

34:31.653 --> 34:34.447
I tempered the blade
yesterday in the oven,

34:34.447 --> 34:36.825
but I feel like
I maybe half did the job,

34:36.825 --> 34:39.286
so I want to temper my blade
with my torch

34:39.286 --> 34:41.413
to give me peace of mind.

34:41.413 --> 34:43.581
<i>There is risk involved</i>
<i>in a torch temper,</i>

34:43.581 --> 34:47.294
which means that I could lose
the hardness of the blade.

34:47.294 --> 34:50.338
I should see a nice blue
up toward the top

34:50.338 --> 34:56.303
and a little straw moving down
toward the middle of the blade.

34:56.303 --> 35:00.098
<i>I think Seth is going</i>
<i>to try to design a blade</i>

35:00.098 --> 35:02.058
<i>that's going to be</i>
<i>much prettier</i>

35:02.058 --> 35:03.560
<i>and sharper than mine,</i>

35:03.560 --> 35:06.146
<i>but I've sacrificed</i>
<i>a little bit of sharpness</i>

35:06.146 --> 35:09.816
to get a little more meat
behind that cutting edge.

35:09.816 --> 35:11.735
<i>I'm in at about</i>
<i>3 pounds right now.</i>

35:11.735 --> 35:14.946
It's gonna cut, but it's not
gonna be a razor blade.

35:14.946 --> 35:17.949
It doesn't feel horribly heavy.
It really doesn't.

35:17.949 --> 35:18.950
‐ Put her right there.

35:18.950 --> 35:20.619
<i>‐ There's one more thing</i>
<i>to do.</i>

35:20.619 --> 35:22.329
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:22.329 --> 35:24.122
It will KEAL.

35:24.122 --> 35:25.624
[laughing]

35:25.624 --> 35:31.421
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:31.421 --> 35:34.007
‐ Seth, Steven, welcome back
to the Forge.

35:34.007 --> 35:36.718
You fellas have had four days
at your home forges to work

35:36.718 --> 35:39.596
on your finale weapons.
Seth, how did it go?

35:39.596 --> 35:42.807
‐ I feel like it's more of
Napoleon's hunting saber.

35:42.807 --> 35:44.351
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:44.351 --> 35:47.062
<i>That is a piece of 5160 steel.</i>

35:47.062 --> 35:49.981
<i>Made the guard out of brass,</i>
<i>and the bolster's brass.</i>

35:49.981 --> 35:52.150
<i>The handle's</i>
<i>waterfall bubinga,</i>

35:52.150 --> 35:55.278
<i>and I did</i>
<i>a deer antler pommel.</i>

35:55.278 --> 35:56.696
‐ All right, man.

35:56.696 --> 35:58.573
Steven, tell us
what you did with your blade.

35:58.573 --> 36:01.409
‐ Things went pretty good.

36:01.409 --> 36:03.495
<i>I used 5160 for the blade.</i>

36:03.495 --> 36:06.498
<i>The handle</i>
<i>is African blackwood.</i>

36:06.498 --> 36:09.042
<i>The guard is some mild steel,</i>

36:09.042 --> 36:11.002
<i>and did a pineapple twist</i>
<i>on it.</i>

36:11.002 --> 36:14.756
‐ Think it's a $10,000 "Forged
in Fire" champion weapon?

36:14.756 --> 36:16.174
‐ One can only hope so.

36:16.174 --> 36:17.384
‐ All right, gentlemen,

36:17.384 --> 36:19.427
there's a strength test,
a sharpness test,

36:19.427 --> 36:21.388
and up first, the kill test.

36:21.388 --> 36:22.806
Doug?

36:22.806 --> 36:24.557
‐ All right, bladesmiths,

36:24.557 --> 36:27.060
to find out what kind of lethal
damage your weapon will do,

36:27.060 --> 36:30.271
I'm gonna deliver slashes and
thrusts on this pig carcass.

36:30.271 --> 36:32.357
Seth, you're up first.
You ready for this?

36:32.357 --> 36:35.026
‐ Let's do it.
‐ Let's do this.

36:35.026 --> 36:36.528
<i>‐ I'm a little bit nervous.</i>

36:36.528 --> 36:39.197
<i>The weight of the sword</i>
<i>feels good in my hand,</i>

36:39.197 --> 36:41.700
<i>but is it going to feel</i>
<i>good in Doug's hand?</i>

36:41.700 --> 36:45.537
I know it's going to cut,
but how well?

36:45.537 --> 36:52.502
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:09.227 --> 37:11.563
‐ All right, Seth, from
the snotter to the trotter,

37:11.563 --> 37:13.565
every cut with this,
as you can see,

37:13.565 --> 37:17.485
offers a very deep,
lacerating cut.

37:17.485 --> 37:20.071
The only issue is that
your blade did pick up

37:20.071 --> 37:22.574
a little bit of a bend,
but overall, sir,

37:22.574 --> 37:25.535
with the way this weapon
moves and feels,

37:25.535 --> 37:26.911
it will KEAL.

37:26.911 --> 37:29.080
‐ Thank you very much.
‐ Good job.

37:29.080 --> 37:30.915
All right, Steven, your turn.
You ready, sir?

37:30.915 --> 37:33.835
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ Let's do this.

37:33.835 --> 37:36.921
‐ I don't know that I will cut
as well as Seth.

37:36.921 --> 37:38.590
<i>I left more meat on my blade.</i>

37:38.590 --> 37:40.258
<i>I'm hoping that it will KEAL.</i>

37:40.258 --> 37:47.223
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:06.117 --> 38:07.368
[exhales]

38:14.793 --> 38:17.462
‐ All right, Steven, let's talk
about your saber here.

38:17.462 --> 38:19.506
It's a heavy, unbalanced sword.

38:19.506 --> 38:22.467
The minute you pick up,
it wants to pull straight down.

38:22.467 --> 38:23.760
It's hard to wield,

38:23.760 --> 38:26.387
but the weight
of your sword here

38:26.387 --> 38:29.766
will definitely bash in
and cut,

38:29.766 --> 38:31.643
so it will KEAL.

38:31.643 --> 38:33.978
‐ Thank you.
‐ Up next is the strength test,

38:33.978 --> 38:36.523
and we have the J‐minator.

38:36.523 --> 38:37.899
J?

38:37.899 --> 38:39.818
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:39.818 --> 38:42.654
‐ Well, bladesmiths, a saber's
supposed to be a sturdy weapon,

38:42.654 --> 38:45.406
so let's see how yours hold up
in our strength test,

38:45.406 --> 38:48.159
a ram skull chop.

38:48.159 --> 38:50.161
I'm gonna take
each of your sabers

38:50.161 --> 38:53.832
and, with no mercy at all,
bash them into this ram skull.

38:53.832 --> 38:56.334
It's not only gonna test the
overall strength of your knife

38:56.334 --> 38:58.044
but the heat treat
on your edge.

38:58.044 --> 39:00.171
Now, I don't really care what
your swords do to the skulls.

39:00.171 --> 39:01.923
I want to see what the skulls
do to your swords.

39:01.923 --> 39:03.675
Now, Seth, you're up first.
You ready to go?

39:03.675 --> 39:05.552
‐ Swing it good.
‐ I can do that.

39:05.552 --> 39:07.762
‐ [chuckles]

39:07.762 --> 39:10.348
<i>My blade has already taken</i>
<i>a slight bend.</i>

39:10.348 --> 39:12.016
<i>If it takes a bigger bend</i>

39:12.016 --> 39:13.685
in this part of the test,
that's it.

39:13.685 --> 39:15.270
They're gonna be
sending me home.

39:15.270 --> 39:16.771
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:31.828 --> 39:33.788
‐ All right, Seth,
your edge held up,

39:33.788 --> 39:35.456
but we do have a bigger bend
in the blade

39:35.456 --> 39:36.541
than we had before.

39:36.541 --> 39:39.878
Your guard is now mobile,

39:39.878 --> 39:41.838
and both of your bolsters
came off as well,

39:41.838 --> 39:44.674
so this mechanical connection
right in here failed,

39:44.674 --> 39:46.217
but the connection
between your blade

39:46.217 --> 39:48.344
and your handle
is still sturdy.

39:48.344 --> 39:49.762
You took some damage,
but you survived.

39:49.762 --> 39:51.556
Good job.
‐ Thank you, sir.

39:51.556 --> 39:54.809
‐ Steve, after seeing that,
how do you feel?

39:54.809 --> 39:56.477
‐ I don't know.
Let's see.

39:56.477 --> 39:58.146
‐ Okay, we'll see.

39:58.146 --> 39:59.439
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:59.439 --> 40:01.274
‐ If I can make it
through this test

40:01.274 --> 40:04.611
without taking a lot of damage,
I think it could put me on top.

40:04.611 --> 40:11.618
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:16.164 --> 40:17.999
[metal clanging]

40:17.999 --> 40:20.168
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:20.168 --> 40:21.711
Dadgum.

40:24.172 --> 40:25.965
‐ Well, Steve, we obviously
have a problem here.

40:25.965 --> 40:28.176
You got a very coarse
grain structure in here,

40:28.176 --> 40:30.053
so I don't know if there
was enough tempering done

40:30.053 --> 40:32.263
on this 5160 blade.

40:32.263 --> 40:34.182
I mean, one strike
is all it took,

40:34.182 --> 40:35.808
and it snapped it
right in half,

40:35.808 --> 40:37.018
so that's obviously a problem.

40:37.018 --> 40:40.980
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:40.980 --> 40:42.649
‐ Well, Steve,
there's nothing left to test.

40:42.649 --> 40:44.692
Your blade has suffered
a catastrophic failure

40:44.692 --> 40:46.694
and can no longer continue
in this competition,

40:46.694 --> 40:48.196
and for that reason

40:48.196 --> 40:51.366
I have to ask you
to please exit the Forge.

40:51.366 --> 40:53.034
<i>‐ I'm upset.</i>

40:53.034 --> 40:55.328
I'm very disappointed
that the blade broke like that.

40:55.328 --> 40:57.455
<i>I'm not coming home</i>
<i>as a champion,</i>

40:57.455 --> 40:59.540
but I'm coming home
a whole lot smarter.

40:59.540 --> 41:02.126
<i>I've made some friends</i>
<i>that I'll have forever.</i>

41:02.126 --> 41:04.712
I would do this again,
no questions asked.

41:04.712 --> 41:08.216
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:08.216 --> 41:10.134
‐ Well, Seth, this is
a competition

41:10.134 --> 41:11.552
where the best blade wins.

41:11.552 --> 41:13.721
Your blade survived
this strength test.

41:13.721 --> 41:15.682
You are the "Forged in Fire"
champion,

41:15.682 --> 41:19.227
and that's a title that comes
with a check for $10,000.

41:19.227 --> 41:20.728
How do you feel?

41:20.728 --> 41:22.981
‐ Surreal right now.
‐ Well, good job, brother.

41:22.981 --> 41:24.607
You're a champion.

41:24.607 --> 41:27.068
<i>‐ I could not be more excited</i>
<i>about this experience.</i>

41:27.068 --> 41:30.321
This competition has been some
of the most fun of my life.

41:30.321 --> 41:32.115
<i>The money's gonna do</i>
<i>some things for the shop,</i>

41:32.115 --> 41:36.995
and my wife and my daughter are
gonna go on a real nice trip.

41:36.995 --> 41:38.162
‐ Good job, Seth.

41:38.162 --> 41:39.247
‐ My name is Seth Borries,

41:39.247 --> 41:41.332
and I'm a "Forged in Fire"
champion.
